00:47:02,980 --> 00:47:05,315
<i>♪  Beneath the lamplight</i>

524
00:47:05,524 --> 00:47:07,901
<i>♪  Parading like court royalty</i>

525
00:47:08,110 --> 00:47:11,112
<i>♪  They're the jewels in our crown</i>

526
00:47:11,322 --> 00:47:15,033
<i>♪  They're our dolls, our clowns, our puppets</i>

527
00:47:15,242 --> 00:47:21,414
<i>♪  Listen in the night to them
sing this refrain:</i>

528
00:47:21,874 --> 00:47:25,752
<i>♪  We're the kids, the kids on the skids</i>

529
00:47:25,962 --> 00:47:28,213
<i>♪  Bums on the street, without a cent</i>

530
00:47:28,422 --> 00:47:31,508
<i>♪  We're the misfits, the down and out misfits</i>

531
00:47:31,717 --> 00:47:34,970
<i>♪  Who were loved somewhere, some night...</i>

532
00:47:35,179 --> 00:47:36,888
<i>♪  They don't have the finery</i>

533
00:47:37,098 --> 00:47:39,057
<i>♪  For the wealthier parts of town</i>

534
00:47:39,308 --> 00:47:41,601
<i>♪  They don't go to the Galeries Lafayette</i>

535
00:47:41,811 --> 00:47:44,187
<i>♪  To ply their trade</i>

536
00:47:44,397 --> 00:47:46,982
<i>♪  Along the Canal Saint Martin</i>

537
00:47:47,316 --> 00:47:50,402
<i>♪  Sebastopol or I. Chapelle</i>

538
00:47:50,611 --> 00:47:52,195
We're like sisters.

539
00:47:52,488 --> 00:47:55,198
<i>♪  For the man who hails them</i>

540
00:47:55,408 --> 00:47:58,576
<i>♪  They're bargain basement goods,
not the finest jewels</i>

541
00:47:58,786 --> 00:48:00,704
<i>♪  You don't find dolls in silks</i>

542
00:48:00,913 --> 00:48:03,540
<i>♪  At the ten cent bazaar</i>

543
00:48:03,749 --> 00:48:07,043
<i>♪  We're the misfists, the down and out misfits</i>

544
00:48:07,253 --> 00:48:11,423
<i>♪  Who sleep in the dirtiest dumps</i>

545
00:48:12,758 --> 00:48:13,758
Did I lie?

546
00:48:14,343 --> 00:48:15,468
She's sensational.

547
00:48:15,678 --> 00:48:17,220
<i>♪  ...nor a single soul</i>

548
00:48:17,430 --> 00:48:19,264
<i>♪  Come what may</i>

549
00:48:19,640 --> 00:48:22,225
<i>♪  We don't give a damn</i>

550
00:48:22,435 --> 00:48:25,687
<i>♪  When the reaper knocks</i>

551
00:48:26,480 --> 00:48:29,649
<i>♪  It's our finest hour</i>

552
00:48:29,859 --> 00:48:32,152
<i>♪  Ring, bells, ring</i>

553
00:48:32,361 --> 00:48:43,163
<i>♪  For the kids on the skids</i>

554
00:49:06,854 --> 00:49:09,606
Meet the venerable Jean Mermoz.

555
00:49:10,524 --> 00:49:12,233
This is for you.

556
00:49:13,569 --> 00:49:14,527
Thank you.

557
00:49:15,029 --> 00:49:16,029
Come, Edith.

558
00:49:17,698 --> 00:49:20,450
You wowed them, you'll do it
tomorrow and every night.

559
00:49:20,993 --> 00:49:23,495
You must meet someone who'll help you.

560
00:49:28,834 --> 00:49:31,544
My name's Marguerite Monnot. I'm a pianist.

561
00:49:31,796 --> 00:49:35,215
If ever you need, I'd love to compose for you.

562
00:49:35,508 --> 00:49:36,257
Thank you.

563
00:49:36,675 --> 00:49:37,634
Come.

564
00:49:38,469 --> 00:49:39,427
Edith,

565
00:49:39,845 --> 00:49:42,055
this is Mr. Jacques Canetti.

566
00:49:42,264 --> 00:49:44,349
Artistic Director of City Radio.

567
00:49:44,558 --> 00:49:47,227
Miss, you completely dazzled me.

568
00:49:47,645 --> 00:49:48,520
Thank you.

569
00:49:48,938 --> 00:49:50,605
Please join us at our table.

570
00:49:51,232 --> 00:49:53,108
I can't stay. I have to run.

571
00:49:53,317 --> 00:49:55,151
What's so important?

572
00:49:57,154 --> 00:49:58,196
Thank you.

573
00:49:58,697 --> 00:49:59,697
What is it?

574
00:49:59,949 --> 00:50:02,033
Marvelous, marvelous.

575
00:50:10,501 --> 00:50:14,754
You better lay off,
or it's pow right in the kisser!

576
00:50:15,005 --> 00:50:17,382
You dimwit, we've been waiting an hour!

577
00:50:17,633 --> 00:50:19,926
Fuck off, you stingy bastard!

578
00:50:24,640 --> 00:50:25,515
Fork it over.

579
00:50:40,906 --> 00:50:43,908
"The Little Sparrow"

580
00:51:18,194 --> 00:51:19,027
Miss...

581
00:51:19,528 --> 00:51:21,237
you're marvelous.

582
00:51:22,323 --> 00:51:24,949
My hand's going to fall off.

583
00:51:25,159 --> 00:51:26,576
Have more bubbly.

584
00:51:26,785 --> 00:51:28,828
I want the bottle!

585
00:51:29,330 --> 00:51:29,996
Here.

586
00:51:30,206 --> 00:51:31,873
I told her to trust me.

587
00:51:32,082 --> 00:51:34,542
That's the power of radio, right, Coquatrix?

588
00:51:34,752 --> 00:51:37,378
Don't forget the magic of musical hall.

589
00:51:37,588 --> 00:51:38,129
Of course.

590
00:51:38,339 --> 00:51:40,882
Edith, I have something for you.

591
00:51:41,091 --> 00:51:43,259
- A song?
- Naturally.

592
00:51:43,552 --> 00:51:44,886
Raymond! Raymond!

593
00:51:45,387 --> 00:51:47,180
Mireille, call Raymond.

594
00:51:49,058 --> 00:51:52,936
Someone for you, Kid.

595
00:51:56,941 --> 00:51:58,441
The big guy wants to talk to you.

596
00:52:00,027 --> 00:52:02,528
This is Raymond Asso,

597
00:52:02,738 --> 00:52:05,740
writer, composer, performer, poet.

598
00:52:06,742 --> 00:52:07,992
I'll be back.

599
00:52:08,202 --> 00:52:09,953
I love your music.

600
00:52:10,537 --> 00:52:13,456
Yeah, I don't like your mug.

601
00:52:19,255 --> 00:52:20,505
I've seen you often.

602
00:52:22,132 --> 00:52:23,800
You must've been hiding.

603
00:52:25,427 --> 00:52:27,303
It's midnight, everyone up.

604
00:52:27,513 --> 00:52:29,222
Everyone stand up!

605
00:52:46,907 --> 00:52:48,199
You're an immense artist.

606
00:52:48,909 --> 00:52:50,368
I'm wearing high heels.

607
00:52:56,709 --> 00:52:57,750
Whenever you'd like...

608
00:52:58,544 --> 00:52:59,752
Call me. I'll be waiting.

609
00:53:20,733 --> 00:53:23,484
My Daddy Leplee!

610
00:53:24,153 --> 00:53:27,655
A toast to my Daddy Leplee, my savior!

611
00:54:40,187 --> 00:54:43,856
What about yesterday? Were you in, or...

612
00:54:44,066 --> 00:54:46,150
I was here, but didn't see him.

613
00:55:25,482 --> 00:55:27,733
You're a bird of ill omen!

614
00:55:33,782 --> 00:55:35,116
It's her fault!

615
00:55:42,416 --> 00:55:43,541
Are you the Little Sparrow?

616
00:55:46,587 --> 00:55:48,129
Follow me, please.

617
00:55:48,881 --> 00:55:49,881
What for?

618
00:55:50,257 --> 00:55:51,257
This way.

619
00:55:52,050 --> 00:55:54,177
Let me through, please.

620
00:55:54,386 --> 00:55:55,219
This way.

621
00:55:55,596 --> 00:55:58,055
I'm talking to you!

622
00:55:58,640 --> 00:56:00,975
- Are you mixed up with The Mob?
- No.

623
00:56:02,811 --> 00:56:04,061
Leave me alone.

624
00:56:04,271 --> 00:56:05,646
What about Henri Valette?

625
00:56:05,856 --> 00:56:08,774
And Georges, Johnny the sailor and Albert...

626
00:56:08,984 --> 00:56:10,234
never heard of them either?

627
00:56:10,903 --> 00:56:13,738
They're friends... they're not mixed up in this.

628
00:56:14,531 --> 00:56:16,908
Aiding and abetting is a crime.

629
00:56:17,242 --> 00:56:19,994
I'm not guilty! I didn't do anything!

630
00:56:20,496 --> 00:56:22,079
I've lost everything.

631
00:56:22,289 --> 00:56:23,498
Where were you last night?

632
00:56:23,957 --> 00:56:26,375
I told you, I was out partying...

633
00:56:28,378 --> 00:56:30,463
You scum, lousy rats!

634
00:56:30,672 --> 00:56:32,340
What you're doing is disgusting!

635
00:56:32,549 --> 00:56:34,675
This isn't the stage!

636
00:56:34,885 --> 00:56:38,346
It seems you have some unsavory friends,
like Albert.

637
00:56:38,555 --> 00:56:41,390
I don't know any of them, lnspector.

638
00:56:41,600 --> 00:56:43,601
Sure. I wasn't born yesterday.

639
00:56:46,104 --> 00:56:48,648
- Hey Sparrow, a statement?
- Not now.

640
00:56:48,899 --> 00:56:49,982
Let her stew in her shame.

641
00:56:50,192 --> 00:56:53,819
Go back to the gutter, little bitch!

642
00:56:54,029 --> 00:56:55,363
Leave her alone!

643
00:56:55,572 --> 00:56:57,448
It's not her. Get it?

644
00:56:57,658 --> 00:56:59,367
Did you sing to get off?

645
00:56:59,576 --> 00:57:01,786
It's a funeral. Show some decency!

646
00:57:06,250 --> 00:57:08,376
- One last question.
- Vultures!

647
00:57:08,585 --> 00:57:09,794
Clear off!

648
00:57:10,712 --> 00:57:12,547
Out of the way! Get lost!

649
00:57:12,756 --> 00:57:14,340
It's over. I'm finished.

650
00:57:14,883 --> 00:57:17,343
They dragged me through the mud.

651
00:57:19,179 --> 00:57:21,472
Forget it. It's old news.

652
00:57:21,765 --> 00:57:23,516
I didn't do anything!

653
00:57:23,725 --> 00:57:24,934
I know.

654
00:57:27,521 --> 00:57:28,688
Open up.

655
00:57:37,948 --> 00:57:38,698
What?

656
00:57:38,907 --> 00:57:40,241
Simone Berteaut?

657
00:57:41,368 --> 00:57:42,159
Yes.

658
00:57:42,494 --> 00:57:45,288
Miss Berteaut, you must come with us.

659
00:57:46,206 --> 00:57:48,040
What for?

660
00:57:48,250 --> 00:57:53,129
Court order from the judge and your mother
to send you to a girls' detention home.

661
00:57:53,547 --> 00:57:56,340
Effective immediately.

662
00:57:56,550 --> 00:57:58,175
Get your things, please.

663
00:57:58,468 --> 00:58:00,636
It's not true. She stays here!

664
00:58:00,846 --> 00:58:02,430
I have nothing to say to you.

665
00:58:03,765 --> 00:58:06,350
For the last time, get your things.

666
00:58:08,562 --> 00:58:09,979
You want to kill me!

667
00:58:10,647 --> 00:58:13,691
You want to kill me, is that it?

668
00:58:14,151 --> 00:58:15,693
Let me go, I said.

669
00:58:15,902 --> 00:58:17,194
She's not leaving.

670
00:58:17,404 --> 00:58:18,863
Momone!

671
00:58:19,072 --> 00:58:22,617
Edith, don't let them take me!

672
00:58:23,452 --> 00:58:25,536
My things! I have nothing!

673
00:58:25,746 --> 00:58:27,705
You hear, you bastard?

674
00:58:28,123 --> 00:58:39,216
Momone, no!

675
00:58:40,761 --> 00:58:42,345
Daddy Leplee.

676
00:58:45,015 --> 00:58:48,684
Oh, Daddy Leplee!

677
00:58:57,402 --> 00:59:00,071
You killed him! Where's the dough?

678
00:59:02,366 --> 00:59:05,284
What do you expect from a former slut?

679
00:59:47,536 --> 00:59:49,704
Everyone out of my dressing room!

680
00:59:50,330 --> 00:59:51,664
Mamie, stay.

681
00:59:58,755 --> 01:00:01,966
I need a shot, it hurts too bad.

682
01:00:28,285 --> 01:00:29,827
Call the American.

683
01:00:35,125 --> 01:00:37,168
You can come in now.

684
01:00:42,466 --> 01:00:44,341
What a triumph. It was divine.

685
01:00:44,926 --> 01:00:45,968
Doug...

686
01:00:48,889 --> 01:00:50,055
I need some air.

687
01:00:50,515 --> 01:00:53,392
I want to go back to Chalons, with you.

688
01:00:55,937 --> 01:00:59,231
It's four hundred kilometers away.

689
01:01:00,484 --> 01:01:02,026
Go to hell, all of you!

690
01:01:02,778 --> 01:01:04,320
I've had it with you all!

691
01:01:04,529 --> 01:01:07,573
You're exhausted. It's a long journey.

692
01:01:07,783 --> 01:01:11,202
It's always no this and no that.
To hell with that!

693
01:01:30,472 --> 01:01:31,222
Let's go back.

694
01:01:31,932 --> 01:01:33,474
Turn around.

695
01:01:34,351 --> 01:01:36,602
Turn around! You spoiled it for me!

696
01:01:52,035 --> 01:01:54,036
Her blood tests are catastrophic.

697
01:01:54,329 --> 01:01:56,747
She has two broken ribs we can't set.

698
01:01:56,957 --> 01:01:58,207
It'll take weeks.

699
01:01:58,917 --> 01:02:00,376
If she has engagements,

700
01:02:00,710 --> 01:02:02,670
cancel them, Mr. Barrier.

701
01:02:12,180 --> 01:02:13,806
It's tight enough. Get away.

702
01:02:14,808 --> 01:02:17,518
Doctor, give me a shot so I can sing.

703
01:02:17,727 --> 01:02:20,646
Sorry, but my admiration has limits.

704
01:02:21,815 --> 01:02:24,024
Theirs has no limits, neither do l.

705
01:02:24,693 --> 01:02:27,444
Cancel. You're playing with your life.

706
01:02:27,654 --> 01:02:30,614
So? You have to play with something.

707
01:02:31,366 --> 01:02:33,993
You want a new life? Get a new you.

708
01:02:34,870 --> 01:02:36,745
- New what?
- New you.

709
01:02:38,248 --> 01:02:39,456
Why didn't you call sooner?

710
01:02:40,667 --> 01:02:43,961
I was busy. I didn't know
what you wanted with me.

711
01:02:44,671 --> 01:02:47,423
I saw you sing. You've a lot to learn.

712
01:02:48,425 --> 01:02:50,467
You're the first to say so.

713
01:02:51,052 --> 01:02:55,306
In three months no one will call you Kid.
Cabaret life's over.

714
01:02:55,640 --> 01:03:00,853
<i>♪  He had bright blue eyes
that flashed like lightning...</i>

715
01:03:01,062 --> 01:03:02,062
<i>♪  Like a storm in the night...</i>

716
01:03:02,272 --> 01:03:05,858
Like a storm in the night! Articulate!

717
01:03:06,651 --> 01:03:07,902
Again!

718
01:03:09,613 --> 01:03:11,447
<i>♪  He had bright blue eyes...</i>

719
01:03:11,656 --> 01:03:14,199
He had bright blue eyes...

720
01:03:14,993 --> 01:03:16,744
Are they words or sounds?

721
01:03:16,953 --> 01:03:19,705
- What do You want?
- Perfect diction!

722
01:03:19,915 --> 01:03:21,874
I sing the way I speak!

723
01:03:22,083 --> 01:03:23,167
Badly.

724
01:03:23,960 --> 01:03:27,379
You slur the words,
and you don't understand them.

725
01:03:30,258 --> 01:03:31,383
Slower, Marguerite.

726
01:03:31,593 --> 01:03:33,928
It's been 6 hours. Can we open a window?

727
01:03:34,137 --> 01:03:35,262
We'll breathe later.

728
01:03:36,598 --> 01:03:37,598
Again.

729
01:03:41,853 --> 01:03:45,773
<i>♪  He had bright blue eyes that flashed
like lightning. Like a storm...</i>

730
01:03:45,982 --> 01:03:48,943
You don't listen! You're not living the song.

731
01:03:50,987 --> 01:03:53,572
You have to be that woman in love.

732
01:03:55,033 --> 01:03:56,158
Think like an actress.

733
01:04:00,705 --> 01:04:01,747
He's mocking me.

734
01:04:01,998 --> 01:04:04,208
We're tired. We need a break.

735
01:04:07,003 --> 01:04:09,338
He makes me feel like I can't sing.

736
01:04:09,631 --> 01:04:11,632
Who do you think you are?

737
01:04:12,968 --> 01:04:14,802
You can't rest on your laurels.

738
01:04:16,179 --> 01:04:18,180
I started singing at nine!

739
01:04:18,390 --> 01:04:22,434
It's okay. Don't worry.
This is new and difficult.

740
01:04:22,811 --> 01:04:25,396
You must become a performer, understand?

741
01:04:25,814 --> 01:04:27,231
Live the song!

742
01:04:28,692 --> 01:04:30,859
No one ever minded my diction.

743
01:04:31,236 --> 01:04:33,696
No one... like who?

744
01:04:34,739 --> 01:04:37,032
Creeps at Gerny's or on the street?

745
01:04:46,459 --> 01:04:48,752
Do what I say or go back to the gutter.

746
01:04:55,844 --> 01:04:57,761
Edith!

747
01:05:04,894 --> 01:05:07,938
To my little girl who never forgot her daddy.

748
01:05:08,148 --> 01:05:10,065
To the Kid!

749
01:05:10,275 --> 01:05:13,444
Heard you got a mentor. Does he have bucks?

750
01:05:13,653 --> 01:05:15,863
Not a cent... it's art for art's sake.

751
01:05:16,072 --> 01:05:18,615
Art for your ass's sake.

752
01:05:18,825 --> 01:05:21,035
Come on, Kid, sing something.

753
01:05:21,286 --> 01:05:31,920
Give us a song!

754
01:05:32,130 --> 01:05:35,466
<i>♪  A woman that looks like a man</i>

755
01:05:35,717 --> 01:05:39,386
<i>♪  Stands no chance of making a killing</i>

756
01:05:39,596 --> 01:05:43,057
<i>♪  'Cos it's really the swish of her skirt</i>

757
01:05:43,266 --> 01:05:46,810
<i>♪  That makes any young lady so thrilling!</i>

758
01:05:47,020 --> 01:05:50,773
<i>♪  When a fella hears this swish swish</i>

759
01:05:50,982 --> 01:05:54,276
<i>♪  What he'll dare do is amazing</i>

760
01:05:54,486 --> 01:05:58,155
<i>♪  His view of the world gets all rosy</i>

761
01:05:58,364 --> 01:06:01,992
<i>♪  With excitement, his pulse starts racing!</i>

762
01:06:02,202 --> 01:06:05,579
<i>♪  Swish swish, swish swish</i>

763
01:06:05,789 --> 01:06:09,124
<i>♪  When she starts her little swish</i>

764
01:06:09,334 --> 01:06:12,795
<i>♪  Swish swish, swish swish</i>

765
01:06:13,004 --> 01:06:15,506
<i>♪  She's quite a dish...</i>

766
01:06:15,715 --> 01:06:17,633
That's the way to handle her.

767
01:06:18,593 --> 01:06:20,302
I let her get away.

768
01:06:22,305 --> 01:06:24,056
I was too good to her!

769
01:06:50,500 --> 01:06:52,835
You're stiff as a poker.

770
01:06:53,628 --> 01:06:54,795
Lifeless.

771
01:06:55,004 --> 01:06:55,963
Like a champ brawling in the street.

772
01:06:56,172 --> 01:06:57,464
Performing is an art.

773
01:06:58,716 --> 01:07:00,634
Grab them with all you've got.

774
01:07:01,803 --> 01:07:03,178
You have great hands.

775
01:07:03,930 --> 01:07:04,888
Use them.

776
01:07:05,557 --> 01:07:06,598
Sing with them.

777
01:07:07,058 --> 01:07:08,267
Again, Marguerite.

778
01:07:13,356 --> 01:07:14,690
Put some life in it.

779
01:07:16,943 --> 01:07:18,068
Your hands, your hands.

780
01:07:22,031 --> 01:07:23,240
That's it.

781
01:07:25,910 --> 01:07:27,494
- I feel stupid.
- Keep going.

782
01:07:38,464 --> 01:07:39,548
Put this on.

783
01:07:40,925 --> 01:07:44,428
People don't care about that.
They like my voice.

784
01:07:44,637 --> 01:07:48,015
How can you be so talented and so pig headed?

785
01:08:15,126 --> 01:08:17,544
- Open up.
- I'm going to throw up!

786
01:08:17,754 --> 01:08:19,129
What's up, is she drunk?

787
01:08:19,339 --> 01:08:20,464
No, she's panicking.

788
01:08:22,759 --> 01:08:24,426
The audience is waiting!

789
01:08:27,931 --> 01:08:30,182
For weeks you bugged me for this show.

790
01:08:30,391 --> 01:08:33,936
Get her on stage before there's a riot!

791
01:08:34,145 --> 01:08:35,479
She's coming.

792
01:08:36,981 --> 01:08:37,689
Edith...

793
01:08:38,316 --> 01:08:39,858
You have three minutes.

794
01:08:40,360 --> 01:08:43,570
This isn't a cabaret, it's a music hall.

795
01:08:44,155 --> 01:08:45,864
What have I gotten myself into?

796
01:08:47,492 --> 01:08:50,369
It's stage fright. It's a good sign.

797
01:08:55,959 --> 01:08:56,959
Edith?

798
01:08:58,378 --> 01:08:59,378
Yes?

799
01:09:01,547 --> 01:09:02,631
This is it.

800
01:09:02,924 --> 01:09:05,008
This is what we've worked for.

801
01:09:05,510 --> 01:09:07,094
You can't crack up now.

802
01:09:10,056 --> 01:09:11,598
Open this door.

803
01:09:12,934 --> 01:09:14,685
No, I can't.

804
01:09:17,355 --> 01:09:18,438
Open it, please.

805
01:09:22,944 --> 01:09:24,027
Stand up.

806
01:12:14,198 --> 01:12:17,492
Ladies and gentlemen, Edith Piaf!

807
01:12:25,126 --> 01:12:26,793
"Edith Piaf Triumphs"

808
01:12:27,003 --> 01:12:29,045
"Street Singer Makes It Big"

809
01:12:29,255 --> 01:12:31,631
"The Little Sparrow Premieres"

810
01:12:33,885 --> 01:12:35,886
"The First Man To Give Me a Hand"

811
01:12:38,890 --> 01:12:40,098
"Piaf On Tour"

812
01:12:45,938 --> 01:12:48,482
"Edith Piaf's sings at the A.B.C. Theater"

813
01:13:04,207 --> 01:13:06,291
"The Sparrow's Dead Long Live Edith Piaf!"

814
01:13:22,767 --> 01:13:24,893
"Do you know what it's like to hurry home..."

815
01:13:25,269 --> 01:13:27,479
"hoping to lean on the one you love,"

816
01:13:27,813 --> 01:13:29,314
"only to find an empty room?"

817
01:13:29,732 --> 01:13:31,525
"Waiting and waiting."

818
01:13:31,734 --> 01:13:33,902
"I know that empty room. Yes, I do."

819
01:13:34,111 --> 01:13:35,779
I can't wait to see you in the play.

820
01:13:37,323 --> 01:13:38,532
Heads up, Canetti's coming.

821
01:13:38,741 --> 01:13:42,035
The conductor has been waiting three hours.

822
01:13:42,245 --> 01:13:42,869
So?

823
01:13:43,079 --> 01:13:45,497
The premiere's in less than 48 hours.

824
01:13:45,706 --> 01:13:49,084
Know many people Cocteau
has written plays for?

825
01:13:50,127 --> 01:13:51,836
- Miss?
- Yes, Suzanne.

826
01:13:52,088 --> 01:13:56,091
Paul Meurisse called.
Dinner with Mr. Cocteau is at 8:00 pm.

827
01:13:56,300 --> 01:13:57,300
You see.

828
01:13:58,052 --> 01:14:00,053
Ask him to come back at midnight.

829
01:14:00,263 --> 01:14:01,638
Are you sure?

830
01:14:01,847 --> 01:14:04,808
You're worse than Raymond. Do this, do that.

831
01:14:05,017 --> 01:14:05,809
Stop it.

832
01:14:06,018 --> 01:14:08,687
- She fired that pain in the ass!
- Stop it.

833
01:14:08,980 --> 01:14:10,438
Shall I show you the gowns?

834
01:14:11,023 --> 01:14:12,566
Yes, the gowns.

835
01:14:20,283 --> 01:14:22,784
They're all here, Miss Piaf.

836
01:14:23,160 --> 01:14:24,661
Careful of the pins.

837
01:14:25,329 --> 01:14:27,289
The simplest one, no collar.

838
01:14:31,210 --> 01:14:34,254
A man's been calling...
He has something for you.

839
01:14:34,463 --> 01:14:36,298
- What's he like?
- A soldier.

840
01:14:36,549 --> 01:14:38,300
I said you couldn't see him.

841
01:14:38,509 --> 01:14:41,177
He's on the landing. It's awkward.

842
01:14:41,387 --> 01:14:43,013
Since he's here, show him in.

843
01:14:51,814 --> 01:14:52,897
Follow me.

844
01:14:55,234 --> 01:14:56,234
Put it there.

845
01:15:00,948 --> 01:15:01,781
Here she is.

846
01:15:01,991 --> 01:15:04,367
Much better with no collar.

847
01:15:05,453 --> 01:15:06,494
Well...

848
01:15:07,246 --> 01:15:10,290
My name's Michel Emer, I'm a corporal.

849
01:15:10,499 --> 01:15:12,584
This isn't the army. What do you want?

850
01:15:16,881 --> 01:15:18,131
I have a song for you.

851
01:15:18,466 --> 01:15:21,217
Another? I have plenty.

852
01:15:21,427 --> 01:15:23,470
I premiere at the Bobino in two days.

853
01:15:23,679 --> 01:15:25,013
I'll take this one.

854
01:15:25,348 --> 01:15:26,765
I go to the front tomorrow.

855
01:15:31,437 --> 01:15:33,563
There's the piano. You have five minutes.

856
01:15:38,819 --> 01:15:39,778
Edith...

857
01:15:43,115 --> 01:15:44,491
We'll have to wait.

858
01:15:51,624 --> 01:15:55,919
<i>♪  The hooker's quite a looker,
standing in the corner</i>

859
01:15:56,212 --> 01:16:00,715
<i>♪  She's got plenty of customers,
and money in her garter</i>

860
01:16:01,008 --> 01:16:05,178
<i>♪  When she calls it a day,
she too goes away</i>

861
01:16:05,388 --> 01:16:11,351
<i>♪  In search of some romance
at a working class dancehall</i>

862
01:16:11,811 --> 01:16:14,896
<i>♪  She listens to the Java,
but doesn't do the dance</i>

863
01:16:15,106 --> 01:16:17,565
<i>♪  ldling near the dance floor</i>

864
01:16:17,775 --> 01:16:20,652
<i>♪  Her love struck gaze is
on the artist who plays</i>

865
01:16:20,861 --> 01:16:22,654
<i>♪  And his long and flashing fingers...</i>

866
01:16:22,863 --> 01:16:23,905
Stop.

867
01:16:26,242 --> 01:16:27,242
I want it.

868
01:16:28,119 --> 01:16:29,327
Everybody out.

869
01:16:29,578 --> 01:16:34,332
You can't do this. We're already late.

870
01:16:34,542 --> 01:16:35,875
What can't she do?

871
01:16:36,293 --> 01:16:38,628
Play it. I want it for the Bobino.

872
01:16:39,505 --> 01:16:40,463
Get moving.

873
01:16:43,092 --> 01:16:44,300
You can't do this.

874
01:16:44,510 --> 01:16:48,304
I can't? Then what's the point
of being Edith Piaf?

875
01:16:56,981 --> 01:16:58,440
In French, please.

876
01:16:58,649 --> 01:17:01,025
She's too desperate, too poor...

877
01:17:01,610 --> 01:17:03,111
Spit it out, Charles.

878
01:17:03,320 --> 01:17:04,195
I'm not a translator.

879
01:17:05,531 --> 01:17:07,532
Pathetic.

880
01:17:07,783 --> 01:17:11,161
Not in the tradition of
the French Cancan and Gay Paree.

881
01:17:11,704 --> 01:17:12,912
A complete flop.

882
01:17:13,164 --> 01:17:16,332
It's not the first time you've had to fight.

883
01:17:17,168 --> 01:17:20,336
Americans want beauties, not me.

884
01:17:20,546 --> 01:17:23,548
I'm not the Parisian bombshell they expected.

885
01:17:23,758 --> 01:17:25,800
Can you see me as a chorus girl?

886
01:17:26,010 --> 01:17:28,511
Where's my feather up the ass!

887
01:17:36,020 --> 01:17:38,438
Go on laugh. I don't connect with them.

888
01:17:38,647 --> 01:17:40,774
I'm too sad, they're too dumb.

889
01:17:40,983 --> 01:17:42,525
Yeah, too dumb.

890
01:17:51,994 --> 01:17:53,328
You're on the front page.

891
01:17:53,537 --> 01:17:54,496
Two columns.

892
01:18:10,179 --> 01:18:12,013
It's Greek to me, translate this shit.

893
01:18:12,223 --> 01:18:16,559
He says they shouldn't let you go.

894
01:18:16,769 --> 01:18:18,770
It would be a grave mistake.

895
01:18:18,979 --> 01:18:21,815
The Americans don't deserve you.

896
01:18:22,650 --> 01:18:25,985
I knew something would happen!
I must get changed.

897
01:18:26,195 --> 01:18:27,904
Ginou, help me choose a dress.

898
01:18:30,282 --> 01:18:32,992
Tonight I'm going out. I have a date.

899
01:18:47,716 --> 01:18:48,842
What's this, Marcel?

900
01:18:49,051 --> 01:18:50,885
Beef... Go on, taste it.

901
01:18:53,973 --> 01:18:55,181
It smells like a wet dog.

902
01:18:59,895 --> 01:19:00,603
What?

903
01:19:07,236 --> 01:19:09,445
Your English is as good as the meat.

904
01:19:17,162 --> 01:19:18,454
Don't like the place?

905
01:19:19,874 --> 01:19:22,542
I'm a bit surprised. I didn't expect...

906
01:19:23,627 --> 01:19:26,212
When you called to invite me out and said

907
01:19:26,422 --> 01:19:28,631
we were two Frenchies alone in New York,

908
01:19:28,841 --> 01:19:30,758
why not go out to eat,

909
01:19:31,719 --> 01:19:33,845
I imagined something different.

910
01:19:34,597 --> 01:19:35,889
It's my local spot.

911
01:19:39,894 --> 01:19:42,854
You sure know how to spoil a girl.

912
01:19:57,119 --> 01:19:58,661
Two pastrami sandwiches...

913
01:19:58,871 --> 01:19:59,954
Oh no!

914
01:20:00,706 --> 01:20:03,958
I'll handle this. Two tournedos Rossini,

915
01:20:04,168 --> 01:20:08,254
and a bottle of Chateau Langelus 1938.
Please.

916
01:20:12,801 --> 01:20:14,135
You must be starving.

917
01:20:15,012 --> 01:20:17,055
Better that than boiled dog meat.

918
01:20:18,349 --> 01:20:19,390
I'm sorry.

919
01:20:20,267 --> 01:20:22,852
Let's start over. Okay?

920
01:20:24,897 --> 01:20:27,023
How long have you been in New York?

921
01:20:27,691 --> 01:20:28,900
Eight weeks.

922
01:20:29,568 --> 01:20:30,818
Do you like America?

923
01:20:32,029 --> 01:20:33,696
I couldn't care less about America.

924
01:20:34,114 --> 01:20:36,491
I don't get them, and they don't get me.

925
01:20:36,700 --> 01:20:39,118
- You must miss Paris.
- Terribly.

926
01:20:39,453 --> 01:20:42,288
What do you do when you're not singing?

927
01:20:42,873 --> 01:20:46,542
You could be a police investigator.

928
01:20:47,211 --> 01:20:48,378
I knit.

929
01:20:49,254 --> 01:20:51,923
Tell me your size, I'll knit you a sweater.

930
01:20:52,174 --> 01:20:54,092
No thanks, really...

931
01:20:56,637 --> 01:20:58,429
Those people recognize you.

932
01:20:58,639 --> 01:20:59,639
Really?

933
01:21:02,643 --> 01:21:07,647
They're saying that chump lost
his last two fights. He's washed up.

934
01:21:07,898 --> 01:21:09,107
I'll shut them up good.

935
01:21:09,316 --> 01:21:10,233
No!

936
01:21:11,610 --> 01:21:14,112
Don't get worked up. I was kidding.

937
01:21:26,667 --> 01:21:27,625
Very good.

938
01:21:38,846 --> 01:21:40,221
Let's not be so formal.

939
01:21:40,431 --> 01:21:41,472
Of course.

940
01:21:42,641 --> 01:21:44,350
And when you're not boxing?

941
01:21:44,601 --> 01:21:46,269
I train, I run.

942
01:21:46,770 --> 01:21:47,895
And after training?

943
01:21:48,105 --> 01:21:51,691
When I'm home in Morocco, I work on my farm.

944
01:21:52,276 --> 01:21:53,693
You have a farm!

945
01:21:54,737 --> 01:21:56,404
I raise pigs.

946
01:22:01,618 --> 01:22:02,201
What?

947
01:22:02,411 --> 01:22:03,411
Why not?

948
01:22:06,874 --> 01:22:08,332
It's true, why not?

949
01:22:08,751 --> 01:22:12,128
It's a lovely farm...
very modern with fine fat pigs.

950
01:22:12,379 --> 01:22:13,629
Who works it when you box?

951
01:22:13,839 --> 01:22:15,006
My wife.

952
01:22:23,807 --> 01:22:24,891
You have...

953
01:22:26,518 --> 01:22:28,019
magnificent hands.

954
01:22:30,564 --> 01:22:31,731
<i>Did you hear that Momone?</i>

955
01:22:32,524 --> 01:22:33,941
<i>It's true. You do have pretty fingers.</i>

956
01:22:36,403 --> 01:22:37,320
<i>Listen.</i>

957
01:22:38,030 --> 01:22:39,363
What color are your eyes?

958
01:22:40,574 --> 01:22:42,992
He leaned over to have a closer look.

959
01:22:43,202 --> 01:22:44,494
And his breath stunk!

960
01:22:44,953 --> 01:22:46,204
You can be such a jerk.

961
01:22:46,413 --> 01:22:48,206
He is a pig farmer after all.

962
01:22:48,415 --> 01:22:49,540
He said...

963
01:22:49,750 --> 01:22:51,209
Violet blue.

964
01:22:51,627 --> 01:22:53,002
Of course, violet blue.

965
01:22:53,921 --> 01:22:55,630
<i>It was the way he said it.</i>

966
01:22:56,256 --> 01:22:57,840
He seemed like a child.

967
01:22:59,635 --> 01:23:00,760
Then he said...

968
01:23:01,512 --> 01:23:02,970
<i>You look like a magical fairy.</i>

969
01:23:04,681 --> 01:23:06,182
That's a bit much.

970
01:23:36,004 --> 01:23:37,088
<i>Did you kiss him?</i>

971
01:23:37,965 --> 01:23:39,173
<i>I didn't dare.</i>

972
01:23:40,968 --> 01:23:43,344
- It was a very lovely evening.
- Too short.

973
01:23:46,849 --> 01:23:48,141
Will you watch me fight?

974
01:23:48,976 --> 01:23:50,434
Of course.

975
01:23:52,813 --> 01:23:54,605
Did he try to kiss you?

976
01:23:55,774 --> 01:23:57,692
Don't know if it crossed his mind.

977
01:23:58,986 --> 01:24:00,403
<i>Yeah sure. I believe that.</i>

978
01:24:00,654 --> 01:24:01,946
I'll come hear you sing.

979
01:24:05,617 --> 01:24:08,578
Well... Good night.

980
01:24:13,000 --> 01:24:14,750
<i>He's the love of my life!</i>

981
01:25:48,178 --> 01:25:50,388
You were wonderful!

982
01:25:50,597 --> 01:25:54,392
Mr. Lucien Roupp who is Mr. Cerdan's manager.

983
01:25:55,227 --> 01:25:56,477
Mr. Jameson

984
01:25:56,937 --> 01:25:58,813
from CBS television network...

985
01:26:13,954 --> 01:26:15,079
Marlene...

986
01:26:18,583 --> 01:26:22,545
Good evening. I'm sorry.
I simply wanted to have a word.

987
01:26:25,382 --> 01:26:27,633
I haven't been to Paris in ages.

988
01:26:28,552 --> 01:26:31,804
But this evening,
when you were singing, Edith,

989
01:26:32,389 --> 01:26:33,514
I was there...

990
01:26:34,433 --> 01:26:36,809
in the streets, beneath its sky.

991
01:26:37,436 --> 01:26:40,354
Your voice is the soul of Paris.

992
01:26:41,148 --> 01:26:42,898
You took me on a journey.

993
01:26:43,608 --> 01:26:45,234
You made me cry.

994
01:26:46,820 --> 01:26:48,946
Thank you from the bottom of my heart.

995
01:26:49,906 --> 01:26:51,324
Thank you.

996
01:27:29,988 --> 01:27:31,155
Come on up.

997
01:27:37,788 --> 01:27:39,497
I'm starting to like this city.

998
01:27:40,248 --> 01:27:42,208
The stars are out tonight.

999
01:27:43,210 --> 01:27:44,752
Let's go.

1000
01:28:00,310 --> 01:28:01,185
Marc,

1001
01:28:01,603 --> 01:28:03,562
do you know how long a frog lives?

1002
01:28:05,440 --> 01:28:06,857
In fairytales or in life?

1003
01:28:10,112 --> 01:28:13,656
I've never read fairytales... to anyone.

1004
01:28:14,408 --> 01:28:16,075
You haven't had the opportunity.

1005
01:28:18,078 --> 01:28:20,788
Yes, but still, I never have.

1006
01:28:49,812 --> 01:28:52,335
<i>♪ The prostitute is alone</i>

1007
01:28:52,660 --> 01:28:54,736
<i>♪ Over there on the corner</i>

1008
01:28:55,836 --> 01:28:58,167
<i>♪ The girls who are sulking</i>

1009
01:28:58,292 --> 01:29:00,460
<i>♪ The men don't want</i>

1010
01:29:01,460 --> 01:29:03,560
<i>♪ And too bad if she dies</i>

1011
01:29:03,885 --> 01:29:05,284
<i>♪ ...</i>

1012
01:29:05,684 --> 01:29:07,623
<i>♪ Farewell to all of those beautiful dreams</i>

1013
01:29:07,848 --> 01:29:10,108
<i>♪ Her life is fu...</i>

1014
01:29:12,380 --> 01:29:14,415
<i>♪ Nevertheless her tired legs</i>

1015
01:29:14,740 --> 01:29:16,704
<i>♪ Take her to the dancehall</i>

1016
01:29:17,700 --> 01:29:19,961
<i>♪ Where there's another...</i>

1017
01:29:21,486 --> 01:29:23,624
<i>♪ ...all night long</i>

1018
01:29:26,560 --> 01:29:28,599
<i>♪ She hears the java</i>

1019
01:29:29,324 --> 01:29:31,584
<i>♪ She listens to the java</i>

1020
01:29:32,800 --> 01:29:34,479
<i>♪ She closes...</i>

1021
01:29:35,804 --> 01:29:37,824
<i>♪ ...wiry and nervous</i>

1022
01:29:38,900 --> 01:29:40,314
<i>♪ It gets under her skin</i>

1023
01:29:40,339 --> 01:29:42,624
<i>♪ From... From her head to her toes</i>

1024
01:29:42,880 --> 01:29:44,880
<i>♪  ...yell out, it's phyisical</i>

1025
01:29:45,120 --> 01:29:46,168
<i>♪ And so...</i>

1026
01:29:46,293 --> 01:29:49,144
<i>♪ She begins to dance, to turn</i>

1027
01:29:49,160 --> 01:29:51,160
<i>♪  To the sound of the music</i>

1028
01:29:54,591 --> 01:29:56,342
Excuse me. I'm a bit tired.

1029
01:29:58,261 --> 01:29:59,261
I'll be back.

1030
01:30:19,824 --> 01:30:20,908
Lay her down there.

1031
01:30:29,376 --> 01:30:30,209
I'm going back.

1032
01:30:30,418 --> 01:30:31,585
It's out of the question.

1033
01:30:32,045 --> 01:30:33,921
Nobody tells me when to stop!

1034
01:30:34,965 --> 01:30:35,881
What do we do?

1035
01:30:36,174 --> 01:30:38,676
I'm sorry. Have everyone leave.

1036
01:30:39,094 --> 01:30:41,136
- I'm going back!
- No, Edith!

1037
01:30:41,513 --> 01:30:42,388
I must go on.

1038
01:30:42,597 --> 01:30:43,722
It's suicide.

1039
01:30:44,266 --> 01:30:45,349
She must be hospitalized.

1040
01:30:45,559 --> 01:30:50,563
No! Louis, I'm begging you!

1041
01:30:50,814 --> 01:30:53,649
You were just in the hospital three weeks ago.

1042
01:30:53,858 --> 01:30:55,484
There will be other galas.

1043
01:30:56,695 --> 01:30:59,738
Take me back on stage!

1044
01:31:00,407 --> 01:31:02,575
Take me back. I must sing!

1045
01:31:02,784 --> 01:31:05,786
I must sing, Louis. I have no choice!

1046
01:31:07,038 --> 01:31:09,290
Edith, please.

1047
01:31:10,458 --> 01:31:12,918
- Do You hear them?
- Stop...

1048
01:31:14,462 --> 01:31:15,671
Close that door!

1049
01:31:16,339 --> 01:31:17,965
Take me back, Louis.

1050
01:31:18,550 --> 01:31:22,094
Take me back. If I don't sing tonight...

1051
01:31:22,929 --> 01:31:25,931
if I don't sing at least one song,

1052
01:31:26,141 --> 01:31:29,643
I'll lose all faith in myself.
Do you understand?

1053
01:31:45,118 --> 01:31:46,410
Doctor,

1054
01:31:48,079 --> 01:31:49,246
do what you must.

1055
01:32:16,149 --> 01:32:18,984
Not this time, you guys.

1056
01:32:19,778 --> 01:32:22,821
You expect me to fall on my face,
I'm in great shape.

1057
01:32:23,448 --> 01:32:26,158
Tell your papers it's not my suicide tour!

1058
01:32:31,623 --> 01:32:32,873
Padam.

1059
01:32:42,570 --> 01:32:45,270
<i>♪  Padam, padam, padam</i>

1060
01:32:46,100 --> 01:32:49,400
<i>♪  It comes running up behind me</i>

1061
01:32:50,540 --> 01:32:53,040
<i>♪  Padam, padam, padam</i>

1062
01:32:53,864 --> 01:32:57,164
<i>♪  It tricks me into remembering</i>

1063
01:32:57,888 --> 01:33:00,688
<i>♪  Padam, padam, padam</i>

1064
01:33:01,512 --> 01:33:03,612
<i>♪  It's a tune that points me...</i>

1065
01:34:03,757 --> 01:34:06,675
<i>Saint Theresa, first of all thank you...</i>

1066
01:34:08,011 --> 01:34:10,512
<i>I know you're behind all this.</i>

1067
01:34:10,847 --> 01:34:12,723
<i>You sent him to me.</i>

1068
01:34:13,933 --> 01:34:17,436
<i>I've found love, and I know it's your doing.</i>

1069
01:34:18,438 --> 01:34:21,690
<i>Sweet Jesus, protect Marcel.</i>

1070
01:35:38,351 --> 01:35:39,560
Go, Marcel!

1071
01:35:42,021 --> 01:35:43,021
Go now!

1072
01:35:43,648 --> 01:35:44,857
It's too soon, Edith.

1073
01:35:45,066 --> 01:35:46,942
No, he'll win. I feel it.

1074
01:35:47,151 --> 01:35:49,736
- If there's a problem, you'll look bad.
- What problem?

1075
01:35:52,365 --> 01:35:55,075
If there's a problem, I'll call you. Now go.

1076
01:36:07,630 --> 01:36:08,672
Hurry up!

1077
01:36:25,273 --> 01:36:30,444
Go, Marcel!

1078
01:36:43,499 --> 01:36:45,417
One round!

1079
01:37:00,725 --> 01:37:02,184
Go on, Marcel!

1080
01:37:06,731 --> 01:37:08,482
Kill him!

1081
01:37:47,063 --> 01:37:49,940
- What's happening?
- Zale's injured.

1082
01:38:18,011 --> 01:38:20,178
He did it? He's world champion!

1083
01:39:22,658 --> 01:39:23,992
You look like an angel.

1084
01:39:26,537 --> 01:39:28,205
Not like a fairy anymore?

1085
01:39:35,630 --> 01:39:37,130
You are my champion.

1086
01:39:37,507 --> 01:39:39,633
I want you to be mine for life.

1087
01:39:40,718 --> 01:39:43,553
Nothing existed before you. It's all gone.

1088
01:39:48,768 --> 01:39:49,976
Stay with me.

1089
01:39:55,024 --> 01:39:59,194
<i>My beloved, yesterday before bed,
I crossed off a day,</i>

1090
01:39:59,403 --> 01:40:01,988
<i>a long day, but also short.</i>

1091
01:40:02,698 --> 01:40:05,867
<i>When the plane took off
it took with it my heart,</i>

1092
01:40:06,077 --> 01:40:08,537
<i>my life, my breath...</i>

1093
01:40:08,746 --> 01:40:11,873
<i>My sweet boy, my child, my love,</i>

1094
01:40:12,333 --> 01:40:14,042
<i>your scent lingers in my sheets</i>

1095
01:40:14,252 --> 01:40:17,129
<i>and my heart sleeps constantly</i>

1096
01:40:17,338 --> 01:40:19,339
<i>in the arms of sadness.</i>

1097
01:40:19,841 --> 01:40:20,715
<i>My Darling,</i>

1098
01:40:21,008 --> 01:40:24,219
<i>I love you. What have you done
to make me feel this way?</i>

1099
01:40:24,679 --> 01:40:25,679
<i>I miss you.</i>

1100
01:40:26,013 --> 01:40:30,100
<i>I'm blank, listless,
as though waiting for something...</i>

1101
01:40:30,810 --> 01:40:32,686
<i>Hold me close to your heart</i>

1102
01:40:32,937 --> 01:40:37,065
<i>and know nothing in the world
counts more than you.</i>

1103
01:40:37,733 --> 01:40:42,988
<i>- Return my heart to me.
- All of France knows about us.</i>

1104
01:40:43,197 --> 01:40:47,617
<i>When I'm in a restaurant,
they play "La Vie en Rose"...</i>

1105
01:40:47,827 --> 01:40:49,786
<i>When I see, my love,</i>

1106
01:40:50,079 --> 01:40:53,957
<i>how attached you are
to your wife and children,</i>

1107
01:40:54,375 --> 01:40:56,710
<i>I feel like going far away,</i>

1108
01:40:56,919 --> 01:41:00,922
<i>thinking someday you'll be grateful to me.</i>

1109
01:41:01,549 --> 01:41:05,594
<i>I can't have you all for myself,
and can't live without you.</i>

1110
01:41:06,179 --> 01:41:09,598
<i>God is my witness,
in this affair, I ask for nothing.</i>

1111
01:41:09,891 --> 01:41:11,933
<i>I'm ready to sacrifice all.</i>

1112
01:41:15,271 --> 01:41:17,063
"If one day life tears you from me,"

1113
01:41:17,440 --> 01:41:19,524
"If you die or are far away"

1114
01:41:19,942 --> 01:41:22,319
"Though you may love me, I would die too"

1115
01:41:27,450 --> 01:41:29,034
In three months,

1116
01:41:29,952 --> 01:41:31,494
that's right, in April...

1117
01:41:31,913 --> 01:41:33,371
I'll be a hit at the Olympia.

1118
01:41:33,789 --> 01:41:36,208
With a full house. We'll be flush.

1119
01:41:36,918 --> 01:41:40,545
Edith, your liver cells
are not functioning normally.

1120
01:41:40,755 --> 01:41:44,007
You've been ill. You need rest. It's serious.

1121
01:41:44,217 --> 01:41:46,843
I'm just 44. I'm not in the grave yet.

1122
01:41:47,053 --> 01:41:50,138
With the cancellations,
we have no more assets.

1123
01:41:50,348 --> 01:41:52,432
You're saying it's my fault.

1124
01:41:52,642 --> 01:41:56,228
That's not it, Edith. It's the tax authority.

1125
01:41:56,479 --> 01:41:59,189
We owe 120,000 francs as a first installment.

1126
01:41:59,982 --> 01:42:03,151
It's jaundice! I don't need
to convalesce for 100 years.

1127
01:42:03,361 --> 01:42:04,736
Don't get carried away.

1128
01:42:06,530 --> 01:42:08,657
I want to perform at the Olympia!

1129
01:42:15,706 --> 01:42:16,790
<i>Anything else?</i>

1130
01:42:17,208 --> 01:42:19,960
<i>Yes, we must stop giving in to her.</i>

1131
01:42:20,169 --> 01:42:22,545
I can't always keep an eye on her.

1132
01:42:22,838 --> 01:42:24,798
She left the hospital too soon.

1133
01:42:25,091 --> 01:42:29,052
The Olympia in three months...
It's a disaster waiting to happen.

1134
01:42:29,262 --> 01:42:30,887
She needs these challenges.

1135
01:42:31,389 --> 01:42:32,973
Not losing propositions.

1136
01:42:33,349 --> 01:42:36,518
When I am the one who had to tell
the insurers it's all cancelled.

1137
01:42:37,478 --> 01:42:39,562
We must decide for her, that's final.

1138
01:42:39,772 --> 01:42:41,064
Whether she likes it or not.

1139
01:43:12,013 --> 01:43:13,346
Edith...

1140
01:43:35,578 --> 01:43:38,580
I said to myself, Edith it's all over!

1141
01:43:39,123 --> 01:43:40,999
He's got someone else. You lost him.

1142
01:43:41,208 --> 01:43:42,167
He was having an affair?

1143
01:43:42,835 --> 01:43:45,462
Would I be telling you this if he were?

1144
01:43:46,297 --> 01:43:48,256
After he left the restaurant,
I followed him.

1145
01:43:48,883 --> 01:43:50,383
My Marcel crossed all of New York

1146
01:43:50,593 --> 01:43:55,138
to eat with an old blind black boxer

1147
01:43:55,348 --> 01:43:58,725
he had met a few years earlier. Imagine that.

1148
01:43:59,977 --> 01:44:02,228
Guys like that are hard to come by.

1149
01:44:02,438 --> 01:44:03,980
My Marcel...

1150
01:44:04,440 --> 01:44:07,484
My Marcel! That's all you talk about.

1151
01:44:08,235 --> 01:44:09,277
Nothing else matters.

1152
01:44:13,324 --> 01:44:15,075
But let me tell you, Ginou,

1153
01:44:16,243 --> 01:44:17,285
I'll never have him.

1154
01:44:18,621 --> 01:44:21,873
He'll never be mine.
He won't leave his wife and kids.

1155
01:44:28,089 --> 01:44:29,714
He calls her every single day.

1156
01:44:32,134 --> 01:44:33,676
I pretend not to notice.

1157
01:44:33,928 --> 01:44:35,428
I want him to be happy.

1158
01:44:38,432 --> 01:44:39,432
I'll be back.

1159
01:44:45,439 --> 01:44:46,898
I could've been Edith Piaf.

1160
01:44:48,025 --> 01:44:49,776
There's more to life than songs.

1161
01:45:01,872 --> 01:45:03,748
It's been too long, Marcel!

1162
01:45:03,999 --> 01:45:06,167
Call Orly. Catch a plane tonight.

1163
01:45:06,585 --> 01:45:08,920
A long boat journey would kill me.

1164
01:45:09,213 --> 01:45:10,839
I miss you, Marcel.

1165
01:45:12,007 --> 01:45:14,008
I can't be apart from you anymore.

1166
01:45:15,553 --> 01:45:17,053
Maybe I should go back to Paris.

1167
01:45:18,431 --> 01:45:19,264
Hold on.

1168
01:45:19,473 --> 01:45:21,558
I'm just Madame's lapdog.

1169
01:45:21,767 --> 01:45:22,976
Stop.

1170
01:45:25,396 --> 01:45:27,814
Rum, Coke! Whiskey!

1171
01:45:28,441 --> 01:45:30,233
Everyone treats me like shit,
around here.

1172
01:45:31,527 --> 01:45:33,319
Boozing it up in Belleville was better.

1173
01:45:37,032 --> 01:45:38,366
You've dropped me, Edith.

1174
01:45:39,493 --> 01:45:40,493
Enough, Momone!

1175
01:45:43,456 --> 01:45:44,998
Get her out of my sight.

1176
01:45:50,129 --> 01:45:51,421
I'll be taking the boat.

1177
01:45:52,923 --> 01:45:54,549
Here's to your career, Edith!

1178
01:46:00,514 --> 01:46:03,391
Please Marcel. Leave tonight. For me!

1179
01:46:55,778 --> 01:46:56,736
You sleep late when I'm not here.

1180
01:46:56,946 --> 01:46:58,780
Thank God, Marcel.

1181
01:46:59,615 --> 01:47:00,865
Thank you.

1182
01:47:11,001 --> 01:47:14,003
I'll make you some coffee. Don't budge.

1183
01:47:21,136 --> 01:47:22,512
Let me serve you.

1184
01:47:40,447 --> 01:47:41,781
What are you doing there?

1185
01:48:00,467 --> 01:48:02,010
I knew you'd come!

1186
01:48:04,805 --> 01:48:07,307
Lucien had a rough time buying the tickets.

1187
01:48:13,188 --> 01:48:14,355
I have a present for you.

1188
01:48:18,068 --> 01:48:19,736
You're in bad shape.

1189
01:48:20,112 --> 01:48:21,946
You need sun. You're so pale.

1190
01:48:31,624 --> 01:48:32,707
Ginou!

1191
01:48:34,627 --> 01:48:36,919
Ginou. I'm looking for the watch!

1192
01:48:43,344 --> 01:48:46,262
What's gotten into you?
I'm looking for the watch!

1193
01:48:46,639 --> 01:48:49,265
It was here, in a long red Cartier package.

1194
01:48:49,475 --> 01:48:51,059
It was here, dammit!

1195
01:49:00,486 --> 01:49:01,736
What is wrong with you all?

1196
01:49:02,071 --> 01:49:05,573
I'm looking for Marcel's watch!
Where is that watch?

1197
01:49:10,704 --> 01:49:12,747
I'm looking for Marcel's watch!

1198
01:49:14,124 --> 01:49:15,166
What?

1199
01:49:16,794 --> 01:49:17,669
Louis?

1200
01:49:18,837 --> 01:49:19,962
What's going on?

1201
01:49:22,841 --> 01:49:24,717
You must be brave, Edith.

1202
01:49:26,220 --> 01:49:27,970
Is it Marcel?

1203
01:49:30,099 --> 01:49:31,182
What?

1204
01:49:34,186 --> 01:49:35,770
The plane crashed...

1205
01:49:50,536 --> 01:50:01,587
Marcel!

1206
01:50:12,141 --> 01:50:17,353
<i>♪  Come what may,</i>

1207
01:50:17,563 --> 01:50:22,275
<i>♪  if your love is true</i>

1208
01:50:22,484 --> 01:50:26,612
<i>♪  For I will die too</i>

1209
01:50:26,822 --> 01:50:29,657
<i>♪  We will live on eternally</i>

1210
01:50:29,867 --> 01:50:36,038
<i>♪  In the vast sky of blue</i>

1211
01:50:36,415 --> 01:50:43,129
<i>♪  In heaven all is harmony</i>

1212
01:50:43,422 --> 01:50:46,424
<i>♪  My love,</i>

1213
01:50:46,717 --> 01:50:56,768
<i>♪  Do you believe we love each other?</i>

1214
01:51:14,620 --> 01:51:18,998
<i>♪  God reunites</i>

1215
01:51:19,208 --> 01:51:30,384
<i>♪  Those who loved before</i>

1216
01:51:36,934 --> 01:51:39,018
I don't know what else
to tell you Miss Piaf.

1217
01:51:40,729 --> 01:51:42,271
They say you're the best psychic...

1218
01:51:42,481 --> 01:51:44,023
That may be, but...

1219
01:51:44,608 --> 01:51:47,568
this is your third visit this week.
What more can I say?

1220
01:51:48,237 --> 01:51:49,529
Why keep coming back?

1221
01:51:51,865 --> 01:51:53,658
So that you can repeat it to me again,

1222
01:51:55,869 --> 01:51:58,287
for me to remember why I must go on living.

1223
01:52:00,082 --> 01:52:02,792
He died in the heavens,
so he must be up there...

1224
01:52:26,608 --> 01:52:30,236
Hey Jack Pills! Can you step on it?

1225
01:52:30,445 --> 01:52:31,779
I need some air.

1226
01:52:34,366 --> 01:52:35,491
That's lovely.

1227
01:52:35,701 --> 01:52:38,327
Step on it. Our pin up's melting!

1228
01:52:39,746 --> 01:52:41,664
I'll get a sore throat.

1229
01:52:41,874 --> 01:52:43,499
Then you'll take care of me

1230
01:52:43,709 --> 01:52:44,959
like a good husband.

1231
01:52:45,252 --> 01:52:47,420
The best hubby I've had.

1232
01:52:47,671 --> 01:52:49,171
The first you've had!

1233
01:52:50,591 --> 01:52:53,676
You plan on gawking at us all day?

1234
01:52:56,847 --> 01:52:58,306
I'm sick to my stomach.

1235
01:52:59,099 --> 01:53:02,393
Watch it, you'll ram us into the scenery.

1236
01:53:03,186 --> 01:53:06,230
Let me drive. Stop, I'll drive.

1237
01:53:06,440 --> 01:53:08,566
That way Ginou can throw up.

1238
01:53:13,947 --> 01:53:15,114
Go on, Ginou.

1239
01:53:16,450 --> 01:53:18,034
May I help Madame...

1240
01:53:20,495 --> 01:53:21,746
Go on, Ginou!

1241
01:53:22,581 --> 01:53:25,875
Very good. Bravo!

1242
01:53:30,923 --> 01:53:32,214
Bye Ginou.

1243
01:53:33,008 --> 01:53:34,634
Wait for me!

1244
01:53:38,722 --> 01:53:40,640
You sure know how to drive.

1245
01:53:43,352 --> 01:53:46,062
At least our outing wasn't for nothing...

1246
01:53:46,271 --> 01:53:48,105
We killed a tree!

1247
01:53:56,823 --> 01:53:58,824
Unbelievable, what shitty service!

1248
01:53:59,242 --> 01:54:01,243
Anybody here to take our order?

1249
01:54:02,704 --> 01:54:05,998
Calm down, dear. Don't play the star.

1250
01:54:06,208 --> 01:54:07,541
Tonight you play the Mocambo.

1251
01:54:07,751 --> 01:54:08,668
Really?

1252
01:54:09,044 --> 01:54:11,671
Remind me who's invited us tomorrow?

1253
01:54:11,880 --> 01:54:15,758
Marlon Brando, Ginger Rodgers, Mr. Chaplin...

1254
01:54:19,972 --> 01:54:21,138
What is that?

1255
01:54:23,308 --> 01:54:25,059
We never ordered that crap!

1256
01:54:36,571 --> 01:54:37,446
Don't touch me!

1257
01:54:37,781 --> 01:54:39,782
- Let me see.
- Don't touch me, I said!

1258
01:54:40,450 --> 01:54:41,867
Wipe yourself off.

1259
01:54:44,997 --> 01:54:46,622
We'd better get a divorce.

1260
01:54:51,878 --> 01:54:55,089
<i>How many injections per day, Madame?</i>

1261
01:54:56,425 --> 01:54:57,717
About ten...

1262
01:54:59,803 --> 01:55:02,555
Sorry to be so direct,

1263
01:55:02,806 --> 01:55:04,765
but why are you doing this?

1264
01:55:08,395 --> 01:55:10,062
So my body will shut up!

1265
01:55:14,317 --> 01:55:15,651
When did you start

1266
01:55:15,861 --> 01:55:17,778
these daily injections?

1267
01:55:18,655 --> 01:55:21,657
Five years ago, after the plane crash. I...

1268
01:55:22,325 --> 01:55:26,287
I was becoming arthritic.
I couldn't knit anymore.

1269
01:55:28,874 --> 01:55:31,917
You are seriously dependant.

1270
01:55:32,544 --> 01:55:34,086
An addiction...

1271
01:55:34,296 --> 01:55:35,546
Doctor,

1272
01:55:36,298 --> 01:55:38,674
I'd like my wife to go to rehab.

1273
01:55:41,845 --> 01:55:43,262
I want to get better.

1274
01:55:43,764 --> 01:55:44,805
I can.

1275
01:55:49,936 --> 01:55:54,148
<i>October 1960 - 5 years later</i>

1276
01:56:15,545 --> 01:56:17,296
Danielle, a chair.

1277
01:56:27,432 --> 01:56:28,265
Edith...

1278
01:56:36,108 --> 01:56:37,149
Here, Edith.

1279
01:56:38,610 --> 01:56:39,693
Sit down.

1280
01:56:50,705 --> 01:56:51,747
Bruno...

1281
01:56:57,879 --> 01:56:59,255
There'll be no Olympia.

1282
01:57:07,013 --> 01:57:07,888
I understand, Edith.

1283
01:57:20,443 --> 01:57:21,652
No!

1284
01:57:29,119 --> 01:57:32,788
I want you to meet Charles Dumont, composer,

1285
01:57:32,998 --> 01:57:35,499
and Michel Vaucaire, lyricist.

1286
01:57:35,709 --> 01:57:38,210
They've come back to play their song.

1287
01:57:46,887 --> 01:57:48,679
Be quick. I'm tired.

1288
01:58:07,199 --> 01:58:11,911
<i>♪  No, nothing at all</i>

1289
01:58:12,746 --> 01:58:17,374
<i>♪  No, I regret nothing</i>

1290
01:58:17,918 --> 01:58:22,630
<i>♪  Neither the kindness received</i>

1291
01:58:22,964 --> 01:58:25,049
<i>♪  Nor sorrows grieved</i>

1292
01:58:25,258 --> 01:58:26,884
<i>♪  It is all the same to me</i>

1293
01:58:27,093 --> 01:58:28,177
Stop!

1294
01:58:29,804 --> 01:58:30,971
I like it.

1295
01:58:32,182 --> 01:58:33,140
Go on!

1296
01:58:34,267 --> 01:58:37,353
<i>♪  All my old memories</i>

1297
